00:02:55,445 --> 00:03:00,548
All right, we have one petition to the Honorable City Council of Councilors.

47
00:03:01,088 --> 00:03:08,853
The undersigned respectfully pray for a meeting before the Medford City Council to discuss the lack of progress of the Medford Clerical Employees Association bargaining unit.

48
00:03:08,873 --> 00:03:13,735
The Medford Clerical Employees Association has been without a contract for three years.

49
00:03:13,775 --> 00:03:19,859
Petitioner Amy C. Tanaglia, president of the Medford Clerical Employees Association, George P. Hassett Drive, 781-393-2509.

50
00:03:22,953 --> 00:03:25,295
Do we have someone who would like to speak on this paper?

51
00:03:25,335 --> 00:03:27,757
Councilor Scarpelli.

52
00:03:27,817 --> 00:03:28,538
Yep, I have that next.

53
00:03:28,578 --> 00:03:31,381
Yeah, absolutely.

54
00:04:09,420 --> 00:04:09,920
Okay.

55
00:04:11,080 --> 00:04:11,300
Okay.

56
00:04:12,021 --> 00:04:13,861
We'd like to proceed or we want to wait a beat.

57
00:04:15,962 --> 00:04:17,002
Name and address for the record, please.

58
00:04:17,423 --> 00:04:20,264
Amy Tanaglia, 85 George P. Hassett Drive.

59
00:04:21,644 --> 00:04:22,384
Go ahead.

60
00:04:22,464 --> 00:04:27,706
I would like to start with thanking the council for giving us a chance to explain our situation.

61
00:04:28,767 --> 00:04:32,208
We have been without a contract for three and a half years.

62
00:04:33,980 --> 00:04:39,124
There's been no increase, there's been discussions, and everything has been shot down.

63
00:04:39,905 --> 00:04:47,411
While the cost of living has gone up over 8%, we're asking for these raises in order to survive.

64
00:04:48,352 --> 00:04:57,600
The cost of living in Massachusetts has skyrocketed, and every time we've gone in front of anybody to ask for a raise, we were told that we would bankrupt the city.

65
00:04:58,772 --> 00:05:08,238
With the rising costs of housing, utilities, gas, food, and medicine, it's making it impossible for us to survive on the wages that we're making.

66
00:05:08,939 --> 00:05:11,800
Currently we are the lowest paid clerks in the city.

67
00:05:13,622 --> 00:05:16,463
During coven we were the ones that kept the city running.

68
00:05:19,663 --> 00:05:29,410
The city and surrounding cities shut down, but yet there were departments that made it mandatory that the clerks come in while everybody else worked from home.

69
00:05:30,431 --> 00:05:34,314
The clerks within the city clerk's office showed up for work every day.

70
00:05:35,054 --> 00:05:36,916
They were made to wear masks and gloves.

71
00:05:37,476 --> 00:05:44,021
They had to go out to cars that were parked outside and collect their applications, whether it be for marriage

72
00:05:44,368 --> 00:05:52,154
death certificates birth certificates business licenses, and due to the closures of all the other cities, they were had to make.

73
00:05:53,354 --> 00:05:57,017
They had to take in marriage licenses from several surrounding cities.

74
00:05:59,018 --> 00:06:07,364
The tax collector's office, obviously had to stay open and make sure all the taxes were paid the water bills were collected the building department.

75
00:06:08,657 --> 00:06:15,322
started an online permitting system to make sure that all permits were applied for were issued, and the money deposited.

76
00:06:16,883 --> 00:06:23,629
Morale is absolutely non-existent with the secretaries clerks within City Hall.

77
00:06:24,309 --> 00:06:31,475
We have been disrespected, overlooked, neglected, and underappreciated for several years.

78
00:06:33,154 --> 00:06:40,801
We're starting to wonder now if it's that we're just considered secretaries, or is it because we're women?

79
00:06:42,382 --> 00:06:50,369
Everyone around us has received raises, stipends, increased sick time, but when it comes to us, we get nothing.

80
00:06:52,577 --> 00:06:57,319
We currently have five clerks that are the lowest classification within the city.

81
00:06:57,799 --> 00:07:03,362
We have senior clerks that need reclassification to the next step of principal Clark.

82
00:07:04,283 --> 00:07:06,143
The difference between pay would be $49 a week.

83
00:07:08,453 --> 00:07:13,714
The total would be $12,740, and they still won't do it.

84
00:07:14,534 --> 00:07:30,117
They have created though several new positions and a new department, which budget has increased from 300, it's increased over 350,000, which you gentlemen and ladies have approved.

85
00:07:30,897 --> 00:07:34,438
It's time that we have our departments reclassified.

86
00:07:35,375 --> 00:07:36,716
We never get any answers.

87
00:07:37,436 --> 00:07:39,237
We always get lots of excuses.

88
00:07:40,617 --> 00:07:42,838
They can't meet with the administration.

89
00:07:42,878 --> 00:07:49,041
They had no time to meet with the administration, constantly canceling negotiations that they have with us.

90
00:07:51,022 --> 00:07:58,585
They are very proud telling us that they have given us Juneteenth off and have put it in, that they're willing to sign that into our contract.

91
00:07:59,405 --> 00:08:01,166
But everybody gets that.

92
00:08:01,406 --> 00:08:03,407
That it's not that they're giving it into us.

93
00:08:03,987 --> 00:08:04,948
Everybody gets that.

94
00:08:07,128 --> 00:08:15,755
When we gave our first initial proposal, we were told that the next meeting we had, they would have answers to all our proposals and they would have a set of their own.

95
00:08:16,475 --> 00:08:22,600
They came back rejecting the majority of our proposals and they had nothing to offer us, nothing at all.

96
00:08:23,741 --> 00:08:33,108
We're tired of being treated less than team players where we have proven time and again that we are dedicated employees to this city.

97
00:08:34,449 --> 00:08:36,150
We demand respect.

98
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,023
the respect that is shown to management and our male counterparts.

99
00:08:42,704 --> 00:08:49,008
And on the last note, I have been here and I have been an employee of the city of Medford for 22 years.

100
00:08:49,908 --> 00:08:59,254
I sat down, did the math and figured out for 22 years, I have gotten a raise of 74 cents an hour extra.

101
00:09:00,074 --> 00:09:02,116
How you expect people to survive on this?

102
00:09:02,996 --> 00:09:05,298
There's no way, there's no way.

103
00:09:06,622 --> 00:09:08,924
We need something done and we need it done now.

104
00:09:09,945 --> 00:09:10,385
Thank you.

105
00:09:11,206 --> 00:09:12,507
Thank you.

106
00:09:28,380 --> 00:09:29,101
Thank you.

107
00:09:29,962 --> 00:09:30,962
Any councilors like to speak?

108
00:09:33,124 --> 00:09:33,885
Madam President, if you may.

109
00:09:33,905 --> 00:09:35,126
Councilor Knight.

110
00:09:35,694 --> 00:09:42,440
I think this administration's been very clear about its approach to labor relations in this community.

111
00:09:44,062 --> 00:09:49,947
Quite frankly, we've seen personnel turnover, more frequently than the rooms at the Hyatt across the street.

112
00:09:50,388 --> 00:09:53,251
All right, there's a human resource nightmare going on here in this community.

113
00:09:53,611 --> 00:09:54,612
It's an absolute nightmare.

114
00:10:02,722 --> 00:10:16,129
A couple months ago, we had a representative from local 25 here before us that showed us a package of 40 somewhat various labor charges, grievances, lawsuits that are pending before the city.

115
00:10:16,889 --> 00:10:23,752
So it brought to my attention that yet another employee has been removed from city hall by escort.

116
00:10:24,773 --> 00:10:25,973
That's not the way you treat employees.

117
00:10:27,374 --> 00:10:28,535
If you respect your employees,

118
00:10:29,438 --> 00:10:30,758
You work with them, not against them.

119
00:10:31,118 --> 00:10:36,560
And I feel as though this administration has worked against a lot of the employees in this community as of recent.

120
00:10:40,101 --> 00:10:44,282
How much money did they spend investigating rumors on a DPW employee?

121
00:10:45,342 --> 00:10:49,523
How much money we've spent reinvestigating and rehashing the Brady List issue?

122
00:10:50,823 --> 00:10:53,124
On and on again, it's more about press releases than results.

123
00:10:54,044 --> 00:10:57,805
On and on again, it seems to me that the work that you people do is not respected.

124
00:10:59,063 --> 00:11:08,201
On and on again, it seems to me that three years without a raise, three and a half years without a raise, while other bargaining units are settling and getting raises, tells us something.

125
00:11:09,042 --> 00:11:10,285
It tells us something, all right?

126
00:11:11,773 --> 00:11:19,619
I appreciate the work that you guys do Amy, I worked with you, I was a bargaining rep for your union at one point in time, I think I did better than 74 cents an hour to I hope Jesus.

127
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:23,462
But that's an average.

128
00:11:23,522 --> 00:11:25,484
Okay.

129
00:11:25,744 --> 00:11:35,952
So, in looking at this and the approach that's going forward I mean ultimately the city council doesn't have the ability to tell the mayor to give you more money, but we can stand with you in lockstep and say that this is a good fight.

130
00:11:36,672 --> 00:11:39,493
I want everybody out there to know what is actually being done.

131
00:11:39,513 --> 00:11:42,193
I mean, we sit here day in and day out.

132
00:11:42,834 --> 00:11:46,955
Regardless of who the mayor is at any point in time, we are dedicated.

133
00:11:47,235 --> 00:11:48,695
We're dedicated to our jobs.

134
00:11:48,735 --> 00:11:50,095
We're dedicated to the city.

135
00:11:50,115 --> 00:11:57,557
And I don't think you have the luxury of closing your door and telling people that you're too busy to meet with them either.

136
00:11:57,597 --> 00:11:57,757
Yeah.

137
00:11:58,477 --> 00:11:58,857
All right.

138
00:11:58,957 --> 00:12:02,698
When the general public walks in off the street, you guys don't have the ability to turn them away.

139
00:12:03,158 --> 00:12:05,399
But when you guys have concerns and issues that you want to address,

140
00:12:06,267 --> 00:12:08,628
The door's not open for you to address those issues and concerns.

141
00:12:09,208 --> 00:12:10,868
I, as one counselor, appreciate the work you do.

142
00:12:10,908 --> 00:12:15,290
I know that the city's only as successful as the work that you do and the commitment that you have to being a part of this team.

143
00:12:15,790 --> 00:12:21,532
It's a two-way street, and the administration has to show some of that respect and responsibility as well.

144
00:12:22,632 --> 00:12:32,795
Moving forward, I certainly would never, ever, ever stand in the way of a contract race, a negotiated contract race that the union and the administration have been able to work out.

145
00:12:33,756 --> 00:12:38,941
But it seems to me that right now negotiation is not the approach administration wants to take we're seeing what's going on at the school department.

146
00:12:39,902 --> 00:12:43,966
My teachers have been the impasse has been declared and the teachers contracts negotiations.

147
00:12:44,707 --> 00:12:46,909
That's one of the larger bargaining units that we have here in this community.

148
00:12:54,930 --> 00:13:05,456
The work in this community that, you know, I send my two children to the public schools that sit there with these public employees for more hours of the day than they spend with me awake, right, when you think about it.

149
00:13:06,256 --> 00:13:15,001
So the investment that we're making in our employees here, the investment that we're making in retention of those employees that have that institutional knowledge is laughable.

150
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:17,162
We're losing good people.

151
00:13:18,103 --> 00:13:20,264
More and more, we're seeing good people being walked out the door.

152
00:13:21,404 --> 00:13:24,086
More and more, we're seeing good people saying, I've had enough, I can't take it anymore.

153
00:13:25,123 --> 00:13:25,883
And they're moving on.

154
00:13:26,583 --> 00:13:31,164
And the only people that are suffering because of that are the residents of this community.

155
00:13:32,645 --> 00:13:34,805
I appreciate you guys in the fight that you're putting up.

156
00:13:35,806 --> 00:13:37,286
It's a good fight, it's a fight worth fighting.

157
00:13:38,066 --> 00:13:44,248
And I'll stand with you every step of the way to ensure that the administration takes the appropriate steps to show value for the work that you do.

158
00:13:54,893 --> 00:13:56,295
Uh, thank you, Madam President.

159
00:13:56,415 --> 00:14:04,243
And, uh, Council nights, uh, you know, comments, uh, I think, uh, hit it right on target.

160
00:14:04,483 --> 00:14:17,016
I think that, uh, what we see is over and over again, the most important people in our community, the people that make our community run are the ones that are being neglected.

161
00:14:17,396 --> 00:14:18,097
And, um,

162
00:14:18,938 --> 00:14:32,762
When you're talking to our brothers and sisters that are teachers or brother and sister firefighters or our secretarial staff or other departments that that are crying out and saying how do we, how do we survive.

163
00:14:36,788 --> 00:14:49,135
hasn't met with administration, hasn't tried to figure out strategic processes and try to figure out a way that we can get to a reasonable percentage raise.

164
00:14:50,656 --> 00:15:02,964
When we're told we talk to people and try to get more invested, it's a personnel matter, which we know, but when it's phone call after phone call and person after person and family after family that are being affected,

165
00:15:03,970 --> 00:15:29,126
It's alarming and it's alarming to the point where we're seeing good people walk out the door, whether on their own or with assistance or whether it's teachers that are qualified and our kids love and making impacts and moving to different communities or whether it's firefighters or police officers leaving to go to different communities or our secretarial staff leaving because it's just not worth working.

166
00:15:30,487 --> 00:15:31,688
It's better just to stay home.

167
00:15:32,496 --> 00:15:34,257
And it's just not fair for you.

168
00:15:34,277 --> 00:15:37,239
And it's not fair for the people that need you in your seats.

169
00:15:37,920 --> 00:15:45,265
So I was raised as a strong union member and understanding that

170
00:15:46,842 --> 00:15:54,344
that we're stronger in force and understanding that as long as we all work together, something positive has to come out of that.

171
00:15:54,984 --> 00:16:14,868
So from one union member to others, we're standing with you and hoping someone listens and tries to put something forward in a positive way because I talked to a lot of teachers last night and I feel the frustration and I could feel, when you walk through this door, you can feel

172
00:16:17,552 --> 00:16:21,193
the dreariness, you can feel the negative aura.

173
00:16:21,233 --> 00:16:21,734
And it's sad.

174
00:16:22,034 --> 00:16:24,895
I'm sad because I love this community, I love this building.

175
00:16:25,855 --> 00:16:27,636
And I apologize that you have to feel that way.

176
00:16:27,736 --> 00:16:35,399
So again, as a council, as one council, and I think most of us, if not all, we stand with you.

177
00:16:35,519 --> 00:16:46,944
So we need to find a way to create something to make sure that all of our employees are happy and they're not leaving.

178
00:16:47,620 --> 00:16:53,027
Because I think that you've already, like you said, we've already, we've already proven all of the unions behind you.

179
00:16:53,407 --> 00:17:00,837
We've already proven that no matter what, we're still going to come in, you're still going to work your tail off for this community, and you're still going to do what's best for the city.

180
00:17:01,497 --> 00:17:05,362
And, and I know it's getting frustrating, and it's going to be a time when

181
00:17:06,253 --> 00:17:07,634
people are just going to say enough is enough.

182
00:17:08,294 --> 00:17:22,283
And then when someone needs a permit there's nobody there, or when someone needs a return phone call there's going to be no one there, or the children to walk into a classroom, and they're going to nobody there, or there's going to be a fire somewhere, and we're not going to have enough firefighters.

183
00:17:22,683 --> 00:17:30,108
So these are the fears that I feel, and it's it's frightening so again, I appreciate what

184
00:17:30,840 --> 00:17:37,423
you did tonight for coming up, because I know it's not easy, but we're standing with you, so thank you.

185
00:17:37,643 --> 00:17:38,964
Thank you.

186
00:17:44,906 --> 00:17:45,666
Thank you, Madam President.

187
00:17:46,727 --> 00:17:58,512
My other two counselors have been very eloquent in what they said, and being a former union employer, I think employees need to be treated with due respect, even if you have differences.

188
00:17:59,677 --> 00:18:01,779
You sit down and you're talking, you're eyeing on your differences.

189
00:18:02,399 --> 00:18:03,960
That's what I see as I have been.

190
00:18:04,300 --> 00:18:07,403
I know I see many people in this building worked here forever.

191
00:18:08,103 --> 00:18:10,145
And you are the frontline workers.

192
00:18:10,325 --> 00:18:15,008
I know we have the police and the firemen, the frontline workers, but when a pipe breaks in the street, what do we call it?

193
00:18:15,028 --> 00:18:15,929
We call it the DPW.

194
00:18:16,229 --> 00:18:18,591
When you need your permit, you call, he comes around.

195
00:18:18,951 --> 00:18:21,113
So these are all frontline workers, everybody here.

196
00:18:21,133 --> 00:18:24,295
These are teachers that teach my grandchildren in school.

197
00:18:25,063 --> 00:18:27,105
Everyone deserves to be treated with respect.

198
00:18:27,825 --> 00:18:29,947
And you're not being treated with respect.

199
00:18:30,287 --> 00:18:36,292
And I say, and like my other counselor said, I stand here with you and hopefully we can get this resolved at some point.

200
00:18:45,559 --> 00:18:45,980
Thank you.

201
00:18:46,260 --> 00:18:49,863
Thank you so much for being here today and to all of you who are here today and for

202
00:18:51,057 --> 00:18:55,660
speaking to the public and for speaking to us about what you've been going through and what you're trying to work on.

203
00:18:55,680 --> 00:19:01,443
I really appreciate this update as painful as it is to hear.

204
00:19:03,904 --> 00:19:08,407
Like my fellow councilors, I will heartily stand with you and for your right to collectively bargain.

205
00:19:10,708 --> 00:19:13,330
To the idea that

206
00:19:15,533 --> 00:19:24,897
we can't find the money to pay some of our essential workers a living wage, that that would somehow cause a dire financial situation for the city.

207
00:19:26,477 --> 00:19:35,221
That's hard to hear because I think we all know that the work that you do is what keeps the essential functions of the city occurring.

208
00:19:36,121 --> 00:19:44,885
